        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>FS CMa is known to have a total integrated flux of 70~mJy at 850 micron (band 7) (di Francesco et al 2008), and we estimated the dusty envelope to have a size at least 0.59" across.  ALMA at band 7 with its highest angular resolution of 0.12" will allow us to spatially resolve the envelope structure and image its morphology for the first time.  Assuming the total flux is uniformly distributed over the 0.59" envelop, we expect an intensity around 3~mJy/beam.  While SMA has the sensitivity, it does not have sufficient angular resolution to diagnose the spatial details of the dusty envelope, which may be clumpy because of the fast rotation and intermittent stellar wind.  ALMA is the only instrument currently capable enough for our program in terms of sensitivity and resolution.  We request a 2 minute integration, which according to the OT reaches a sensitivity of 0.14~mJy, in order to have S/N=20 to sufficiently study the intensity profile of the envelope.  We only observe the continuum, so need a standard optimal continuum frequency setup of atmospheric transparency (default 343.5~GHz for band 7).  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
