    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to resolve the dusty circumstellar structure and turbulent environments in FS CMa, the prototype of a class of B-type main sequence stars as cosmic dust suppliers.  This class of stars are fast rotators, and show prominent infrared excess, strong Halpha emission and forbidden lines, suggesting the existence of thermalized dust.  Yet these so-called classical Be stars are away from any star-forming regions, so the circumstellar dust must be formed in situ, in contrast to the case in young Herbig Ae/Be stars which inherit the dust from parental molecular clouds.  The dust in classical Be stars is hypothesized to condense in an expanding envelope which, because of the rapid stellar rotation, results in nonspherical mass loss, likely in a disk-like manner.  Our ALMA observations of FS CMa will provide the first witness of where the dust formation takes place by a massive main sequence star.  </prp:abstract>
